,Recommended,251170,29104997,Posted: 7 January,all,b-rom,"Damned is a flawed game with a tremendous amount of potential.The basic premise is an asymetrical multiplayer FPS horror game.  Four players play people and one person plays some sort of monster.  The monster is invincible and can kill any of the players instantly.  The players need to navigate their way through frequently labyrinthine levels full of locked doors and... well locked doors.  If the monster kills all the players, the monster wins.  If the players find the exit, the players win.  The monsters can only hunt the players at certain times in certain circumstances.  The rest of the time they are trying to keep tabs on the players if they can, and generally keep the players as scared as possible.The things about this game that I love:- As a player, because you have no real defenses of your own, the monsters are terrifying.  Seeing one always elicits an immediate and frantic attempt to escape.- The 3D attenuated sound means that the monsters can really add to the experience by acting in scary (or funny) ways.- The complicated level layouts leave lots of time for the players to get lost, get separated, be hunted, etc.  Games almost always last long enough for quite a few good scares and intense moments.The problems with this game:- Horribly buggy.  We have never had a gaming session that hasn't been marred by game crashes, freezes, etc.  It can be tricky to recover from some of these crashes, and sometimes they'll require a hard reboot.  Also, the game requires a login, and if you crash sometimes that login gets locked in a session meaning you can't rejoin for a while.- The monsters have very little to do in the periods when they aren't being a direct threat.  Sure you can ""place traps"", but that entails nothing more then clicking on objects.  Not particularly exciting.- The players have only one puzzle to solve.  Find the key that fits the door.  And there are no clues as to which key is for what, so not only is it a very boring puzzle, it's extremely tedious as you try every key you find on every door that's locked.  Sure, there are also boarded doors and safes, but they are still the same mechanic, it's just that the key is named ""hammer"", or ""crowbar"" or ""safe code"".- The maps and monsters are terribly balanced.  Some monsters will wipe out the players very quickly.  Others will make for excellent experiences.  Some maps fit certain monsters very well, but fit other monsters very poorly.All in all I want to recommend this game, and have marked it as such.  However, it has some serious issues, and I would caution against buying it without being aware of the issues it has."
76561198028104308,Recommended,251170,10499935,"Posted: 16 June, 2014",all,Haunted Adventurer,"BRIEF SYNOPSIS: You can have great jump scares with this beta 3D multiplayer horror adventure where you play either one of four survivors trying to escape, or a horrifying monster attempting to kill the survivors; recommended despite bugs (see forums). * Spoilers below *GAMEPLAY REVIEW:Summary:My childhood nightmares come to life. I'm a wimp when it comes to anything horror, but the multiplayer adventurer in me as drawn me in. It is brilliant to have four different human survivors as a team versus one human-controlled monster. And the three current monsters are terrifying, along with the ten existing levels full of creepy ambiance and atmosphere.Escape is difficult but not impossible for the survivors, who need to find keys and codes to unlock and open doors and safes, use batteries to power their flashlights, grab a crowbar or hammer to smash wooden boards, and eventually escape the monster or fall victim to it. The longer it takes to complete a level, the more the survivors become insane and the more difficult it becomes to escape.In game chat:I really enjoyed using the 3d audio with a microphone headset. It makes a huge difference in the game. Everyone can hear you speaking, so if you want to keep the monster guessing use the in-game text chat (brought up with the enter key). It's also good with chatting in-between rounds in the lobby.Game play seems to favour the monsters, but smart survivors will be able to team up to outwit their pursuer to escape. Even in death, survivors can text chat with the living to give helpful hints, such as “You missed a key in the sink,” or “I have a crowbar with my body on the main floor.”Lobby:After logging in you can setup your options and either join or host your own game. Hosts can have an open game lobby or set a password to have a private game amongst friends only. Some people have complained about being kicked out of games but I think most people who want private games have figured out how to the use password now. Those of you still kicking people, stop being so lazy and use a password for your private games (May the Lurker devour your soul...). The people hosting and the people I've played with in this community have been courteous and fun to play with. Thanks people for making this game even more fun! Most people seem to be on the servers during the weekends.Life mode seems better if you are casually hosting players – people can join in whenever they feel like if there is a spot. Normal mode is more hard core with only one life to live or die with.Levels:There are currently ten levels consisting of three hotels, three asylums, a hospital (asylum set), a restaurant (hotel set), a warehouse (hotel set), and a factory. Each are different sizes and have different strategies. Some have two exits which help prevent monster camping at the exit. Some have stairs and different levels. Some have too many damn tables. Each level is creepy and atmospheric. I AM HOPING FOR GRAVEYARD TYPE LEVELS FOR A FUTURE UPDATE. There are only three different set types for levels (asylum, hotel, or factory).Survivors:There are four player controlled survivor models:Mia the emo; she appears to be Asian and wears miss-matching shoes.Scott the jockey, sporting his Eagles college jacket.Jacob the nerd; he is of African descent and a little stout.Father John the priest; he totes a Bible but it's not compelling monsters to go away.The survivors typically start in a room and have to find keys and codes to unlock doors and safes that will eventually allow them to escape from the level. The survivors are equipped with a battery burning flashlight that needs to be replenished or they will be forced to grope around in the dark. The longer the survivors take to complete a level, the more insane they will become. Others tools survivors will need include either a crowbar or a small hammer to remove boards from exit or storage doors. [A shovel is needed in the graveyard level.] - oops, sorry, don't know how that got in there... There are no weapons or way to attack the monster, which makes then all the more scary. Repeat, there is no BFG to save you!Monsters:There are currently three monsters that one player can choose to hunt down the survivors. I feel the monsters are generally well-balanced. Some people feel the Phantom is still overpowered, despite all the tweaks it has been receiving as of late. Survivors must adjust their game-play for each monster in order to escape.Mary is the scariest monster and my current favourite. She is a great monster with pretty blue eyes, but she has some posture issues. She seems well balanced with her movements and attacks. Her walk mode is a little slow, but her attack is long reaching and swift. Quick manoeuvring for survivors is the key when you hear her scream. Mary has some movement issues over objects and the Factory catwalk.The Lurker is a muscular hulk with two forms. The first form is spiritual and allows the Lurker to freely roam the level, unencumbered by doors. In this mode it can set sound traps that go off when a survivor is nearby to help it locate the players as it cannot see anyone in this form. Once the Lurker is powered up by time it can enter its physical form where it can visibly stalk and kill remaining survivors. After a while the Lurker will revert to its spiritual form where it will have to wait until it recharges and takes physical form again. The longer the Lurker remains in physical form, the longer it take to recharge in spiritual form.The Phantom is a roaming skeletal ghost (the creepiest monster for me until Mary joined) that can see survivors via sound such as the clicking of flashlights, running, or setting off a trap. Then it's either run away for the survivors and try to escape the Phantoms detection radius or get eviscerated by it. When the Phantom hears a survivor, it can see a white shadow, even through walls or different levels, of where the player is.Traps are set automatically for the Phantom and Mary, whereas setting traps is part of the Lurker's strategy. They are generally objects strewn about the level. Each trap makes a different sound to alert a monster to where a survivor is.Sound:The music is great for a horror game. Each monster has its own terrifying theme music when it appears near a survivor. Ambient sounds like footsteps, breathing, traps, and screams add to the atmosphere. The 3D audio chat really adds to the game-play; it is great to taunt the survivors as a monster. Dead players can only text chat.Insanity system:The insanity system increases game difficulty by darkening a survivor's screen to the point of complete darkness, making the flashlight flicker on and off, causing the player to hear random sounds, losing hearing, losing colour vision, having arms emerge from the ground that slow or halt a survivor's progress, randomly disabling a directional key on your keyboard, and flashing images of possessed survivors across your screen. The effects are temporary but potentially deadly.The insanity mode is a great idea and has been toned down from beta 1.0 to occur less frequently. It serves its purpose of making the game especially difficult the longer the survivors take to exit. Apparently the jump scare faces have been fixed so that they don't blind you, but I have yet to see the new effect since my game currently freezes before it occurs. I feel the jump scares are not necessary in this game. Also annoying for fair game-play is the keyboard/mouse movement disabling effect.CONCLUSION:Despite bugs being ironed out during the beta period, I feel the game is a very enjoyable if not a mildly terrifying experience. It's best played with all five people, and the up to four survivors really need to cooperate to escape from the monster. Recommended for beta and if all bugs (especially game freezing/crashing) get squashed for the retail release.Edited 2014-08-26 - [Version Beta 1.12a]"
