,Recommended,251170,15204201,"Posted: 4 April, 2015",all,RAIZO,"OH THE HORRORS OF SEARCHING FOR KEYS!!  So many keys, so little time.  It's true, there has been a trend in multiplayer horror games lately, namely rogue-likes, that force you to quest for keys.Here's an example, namely of Damned, but for this kind of game in general:>> KEY1 - Unlocks DOOR1>> DOOR1 - leads to KEY2>> KEY2 - Unlocks DOOR2>> DOOR2 - leads to.....wait, no friggin' key, are you serious?!Backtrack a little, oh there's a key you overlooked.  It unlocks a drawer back in the room DOOR1 leads to, thereby       giving you KEY3.>> KEY3 - Get a crowbar.... : /   and where the sh*t am I supposed to use that?! (HINT: when you finally find KEY10 which will ultimately lead you to a special SILVER KEY, then you'll find the boards you're supposed to pry off with said crowbar)All this fetch quest madness leads to a greater sense of fear and unease in the player.  I have to admit, I found that gameplay mechanic annoying and overly tedious at first.  Since then, it's grown on me.  I realize now that if I were in this situation, with 3 strangers (other Steam players) being stalked by 1 of 3 types of monster (another Steam player; that's right: 4 'survivors' and 1 monster make up the basis of the game 'FIND STUFF TO USE ON THINGS AND AVOID GETTING KILLED BY A 'THING' ALONG THE WAY') that I couldn't possibly know where the keys were to get out of wherever it is that we're all trapped in.  So I guess you could say the fetch quest just makes the situation more realistic.All in all, Damned is a pretty fun game and there are trading cards and achievements too. Don't worry, the achievement for successfully completing a certain number of maps goes both ways - you can do so as the monster (so much fun!!) or as a survivor.  Also, the person that plays as the monster doesn't have the advantage you'd think he/she would have.  The monsters have their own strengths and weaknesses, such as the ghoul not being able to see anyone until it's right on top of them + plus it floats around very slowly.  Mary walks slow, but she can teleport too (but even then that's only so many times until the ability has to recharge, in a manner of speaking - you get more charge/uses the more times that you see survivors) and can only go into a 'frenzy' which allows you to take them down by keeping them in your sight long enough to allow it to activate. The 3rd monster can set traps that allow it to pinpoint where survivors are, as it can't see them until it can go into a stalker/kill mode, which of course you have to wait for between each use of said mode.So Damned is pretty balanced as far as this kind of game goes and will offer far more hours of gameplay than alot of other indie/horror games.  Even more fun if you play with friends (which I haven't done personally, but I think it would be fun)."
